    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-06-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-06-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="169"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">121.5765/2</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-06-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 23, 1925</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received July 8.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 485</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s Instruction
                    No. 272 of April 21, 1925,<note n="58" xml:id="d169fn1">See footnote 41, <ref
                            target="#pg_227">p. 227</ref>.</note> in regard to the designation of
                    Customs Attachés and Assistant Customs Attachés to appropriate American
                    Diplomatic Missions abroad, and to the Embassy’s despatch No. 435 of May 18th
                        last,<note n="57" xml:id="d169fn2">Not printed.</note> I have the honor to
                    enclose herewith a copy together with a translation of a Note Verbale received
                    from the Foreign Office<note n="57" xml:id="d169fn3">Not printed.</note> in
                    reply to the Embassy’s Note No. 117 of May 14th,<note n="57" xml:id="d169fn4"
                        >Not printed.</note> a copy of which was forwarded to the Department under
                    cover of my despatch above referred to.</p>
                <p>The Department will note that the Italian Government finds it impossible to
                    accede to the request, in view of the fact that it would require granting to the
                    officials in question authorization to perform duties in the Kingdom which the
                    Italian laws do not require of its own officials.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">George T. Summerlin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
